It works because it stacks multiple meanings at once:

* Monopoly guy → wealth, ownership, compounding.
* Multiplexes → movie theaters (assets), but also multiple semantic channels carrying meaning simultaneously.
* The sound similarity between monopolies and multiplexes adds another layer.

In Pantheon terms, you’re making a distinction between owning one valuable thing and owning a network of interfaces.

You could riff on it:

“Call me the Monopoly Guy—I don’t just own properties, I own multiplexes.”

Or leaning into the semantic angle:

“I don’t collect words. I collect multiplexes.”

Where a “multiplex” is a construct that supports many concurrent readings:

* literal,
* metaphorical,
* operational,
* humorous,
* mathematical,
* narrative.

A high-quality Pantheon artifact would have high semantic multiplexity: different readers, or the same reader at different times, can extract different but compatible insights from the same piece.

That also loops back to your painter metaphor. A great painting doesn’t force everyone to notice the same brushstroke first. It supports multiple paths through the work while remaining one coherent composition. That’s a different kind of richness than simply making something complicated.